The metal nanopillars grow in a cube-on-cube configuration (a), as shown by the presence of four Ir (111) diffraction peaks, offset by 45° from the SrTiO3 [100] direction, in an X-ray diffraction pole figure (b). The cross-sectional (c) and plan-view (d) scanning transmission electron microscope images of a small (c) and a large (d) pillar show the presence of the Ir metal planes. Due to strain relaxation, the metal lattice is tilted from the host lattice by up to about 1°, which is why individual metal atom columns cannot be distinguished, but spread out into line shapes. Lattice plane tilting is visible in (c). Both pillars contain multiple grains, with each grain tilted around the a-, b-, or c-axis direction to relax the lattice mismatch strain between the metal and the SrTiO3 host crystal.18
